WEBVTT

00:20.100 --> 00:21.140
CHAPTER XIV

00:21.140 --> 00:24.260
Some time elapsed before I learned the history of my friends.

00:24.680 --> 00:29.320
It was one which could not fail to impress itself deeply on my mind, unfolding as it

00:29.320 --> 00:34.960
did in a number of circumstances, each interesting and wonderful to one so utterly inexperienced

00:34.960 --> 00:35.800
as I was.

00:36.720 --> 00:38.840
The name of the old man was De Lacey.

00:39.300 --> 00:44.160
He was descended from a good family in France, where he had lived for many years in affluence,

00:44.600 --> 00:47.280
respected by his superiors and beloved by his equals.

00:48.020 --> 00:52.940
His son was bred in the service of his country, and Agatha had ranked with ladies of the highest

00:52.940 --> 00:53.480
distinction.

00:54.120 --> 00:59.460
A few months before my arrival, they had lived in a large and luxurious city called Paris,

01:00.020 --> 01:04.720
surrounded by friends and possessed of every enjoyment which virtue, refinement of intellect

01:04.720 --> 01:08.140
or taste, accompanied by a moderate fortune, could afford.

01:08.840 --> 01:11.300
The father of Safie had been the cause of their ruin.

01:11.880 --> 01:16.700
He was a Turkish merchant, and had inhabited Paris for many years, when for some reason

01:16.700 --> 01:19.760
which I could not learn, he became obnoxious to the government.

01:19.760 --> 01:24.960
He was seized and cast into prison the very day that Safie arrived from Constantinople

01:24.960 --> 01:25.700
to join him.

01:26.100 --> 01:28.240
He was tried and condemned to death.

01:29.040 --> 01:31.440
The injustice of his sentence was very flagrant.

01:31.620 --> 01:36.020
All Paris was indignant, and it was judged that his religion and wealth, rather than

01:36.020 --> 01:39.060
the crime alleged against him, had been the cause of his condemnation.

01:40.200 --> 01:42.300
Felix had accidentally been present at the trial.

01:42.600 --> 01:46.620
His horror and indignation were uncontrollable when he heard the decision of the court.

01:46.620 --> 01:51.620
He made at that moment a solemn vow to deliver him, and then looked around for the means.

01:52.320 --> 01:57.000
After many fruitless attempts to gain admittance to the prison, he found a strongly graded

01:57.000 --> 02:01.500
window in an unguarded part of the building, which lighted the dungeon of the unfortunate

02:01.500 --> 02:06.860
Mohammedan, who, loaded with chains, waited in despair the execution of the barbarous

02:06.860 --> 02:07.360
sentence.

02:08.260 --> 02:12.580
Felix visited the great at night, and made known to the prisoner his intentions in his

02:12.580 --> 02:12.860
favor.

02:13.400 --> 02:18.940
The Turk, amazed and delighted, endeavored to rekindle the zeal of his deliverer by promises

02:18.940 --> 02:20.300
of reward and wealth.

02:21.180 --> 02:23.080
Felix rejected his offers with contempt.

02:23.840 --> 02:28.240
Yet when he saw the lovely Safie, who was allowed to visit her father, and who by her

02:28.240 --> 02:33.340
gestures expressed her lively gratitude, the youth could not help owning to his own mind

02:33.340 --> 02:37.940
that the captive possessed a treasure which would fully reward his toil and hazard.

02:38.520 --> 02:42.060
The Turk quickly perceived the impression that his daughter had made on the heart of

02:42.060 --> 02:47.060
Felix, and endeavored to secure him more entirely in his interests by the promise of her hand

02:47.060 --> 02:50.240
in marriage so soon as he should be conveyed to a place of safety.

02:51.340 --> 02:55.760
Felix was too delicate to accept this offer, yet he looked forward to the probability of

02:55.760 --> 02:58.120
the event as to the consummation of his happiness.

02:59.040 --> 03:03.820
During the ensuing days, while the preparations were going forward for the escape of the merchant,

03:04.220 --> 03:08.660
the zeal of Felix was warmed by several letters that he received from this lovely girl, who

03:09.200 --> 03:14.000
her thoughts in the language of her lover by the aid of an old man, a servant of her

03:14.000 --> 03:15.340
father who understood French.

03:16.100 --> 03:20.640
She thanked him in the most ardent terms for his intended services toward her parent, and

03:20.640 --> 03:23.340
at the same time she gently deplored her own fate.

03:24.300 --> 03:29.000
I have copies of these letters, for I found means during my residence in the hovel to

03:29.000 --> 03:32.860
procure implements of writing, and the letters were often in the hands of Felix or Agatha.

03:33.460 --> 03:35.680
Before I depart, I will give them to you.

03:35.780 --> 03:37.520
They will prove the truth of my tale.

03:37.520 --> 03:42.320
But at present, as the sun is already far declined, I shall only have time to repeat

03:42.320 --> 03:43.780
the substance of them to you.

03:45.080 --> 03:49.340
Safi related that her mother was a Christian Arab, seized and made a slave by the Turks.

03:49.880 --> 03:54.300
Recommended by her beauty, she had won the heart of the father of Safi, who married her.

03:54.940 --> 03:59.380
The young girl spoke in high and enthusiastic terms of her mother, who, born in freedom,

03:59.940 --> 04:02.100
spurned the bondage to which she was now reduced.

04:02.520 --> 04:06.540
She instructed her daughter in the tenets of her religion, and taught her to aspire

04:06.540 --> 04:11.340
to higher powers of intellect and an independence of spirit forbidden to the female followers

04:11.340 --> 04:11.940
of Muhammad.

04:12.680 --> 04:17.620
This lady died, but her lessons were indelibly impressed on the mind of Safi, who sickened

04:17.620 --> 04:21.880
at the prospect of again returning to Asia and being immured within the walls of a harem,

04:22.380 --> 04:26.580
allowed only to occupy herself with infantile amusements ill-suited to the temper of her

04:26.580 --> 04:30.380
soul, now accustomed to grand ideas and a noble emulation for virtue.

04:31.080 --> 04:35.320
The prospect of marrying a Christian and remaining in a country where women were allowed to take

04:35.320 --> 04:37.680
rank in society was enchanting to her.

04:39.280 --> 04:43.660
The day for the execution of the Turk was fixed, but on the night previous to it, he

04:43.660 --> 04:47.180
quitted his prison and before morning was distant many leagues from Paris.

04:48.100 --> 04:51.740
Felix had procured passports in the name of his father, sister and himself.

04:52.260 --> 04:56.760
He had previously communicated his plan to the former, who aided the deceit by quitting

04:56.760 --> 05:00.980
his house under the pretense of a journey, and concealed himself with his daughter in

05:00.980 --> 05:02.460
an obscure part of Paris.

05:03.320 --> 05:08.420
Felix conducted the fugitives through France to Lyon and across Mount Sinis to Leghorn,

05:08.780 --> 05:13.280
where the merchant had decided to wait a favorable opportunity of passing into some part of the

05:13.280 --> 05:14.700
Turkish dominions.

05:15.140 --> 05:19.340
Safi resolved to remain with her father until the moment of his departure, before which

05:19.340 --> 05:24.060
time the Turk renewed his promise that she should be united to his deliverer, and Felix

05:24.060 --> 05:26.180
remained with them in expectation of that event.

05:26.680 --> 05:31.360
And in the meantime, he enjoyed the society of the Arabian, who exhibited toward him the

05:31.360 --> 05:32.960
simplest and tenderest affection.

05:33.700 --> 05:37.940
They conversed with one another through the means of an interpreter, and sometimes with

05:37.940 --> 05:42.620
the interpretation of looks, and Safi sang to him the divine aires of her native country.

05:43.540 --> 05:48.080
The Turk allowed this intimacy to take place and encouraged the hopes of the youthful lovers,

05:48.520 --> 05:50.940
while in his heart he had formed far other plans.

05:51.380 --> 05:55.600
He loathed the idea that his daughter should be united to a Christian, but he feared the

05:55.600 --> 06:00.000
resentment of Felix if he should appear lukewarm, for he knew that he was still in the power

06:00.000 --> 06:04.420
of his deliverer if he should choose to betray him to the Italian state which they inhabited.

06:05.100 --> 06:09.200
He revolved a thousand plans by which he should be enabled to prolong the deceit until it

06:09.200 --> 06:13.540
might be no longer necessary, and secretly to take his daughter with him when he departed.

06:14.420 --> 06:17.520
His plans were facilitated by the news which arrived from Paris.

06:18.060 --> 06:22.480
The government of France were greatly enraged at the escape of their victim, and spared

06:22.480 --> 06:25.080
no pains to detect and punish his deliverer.

06:25.080 --> 06:30.100
The plot of Felix was quickly discovered, and De Lacy and Agatha were thrown into prison.

06:30.800 --> 06:33.680
The news reached Felix and roused him from his dream of pleasure.

06:34.400 --> 06:39.400
His blind and aged father and his gentle sister lay in a noisome dungeon while he enjoyed

06:39.400 --> 06:42.440
the free air and the society of her whom he loved.

06:43.120 --> 06:44.600
This idea was torture to him.

06:44.940 --> 06:49.120
He quickly arranged with the Turk that if the latter should find a favorable opportunity

06:49.120 --> 06:54.440
for escape before Felix could return to Italy, Safi should remain as a border at a convent

06:54.440 --> 06:59.460
in Leghorn, and then, quitting the lovely Arabian, he hastened to Paris and delivered

06:59.460 --> 07:04.600
himself up to the vengeance of the law, hoping to free De Lacy and Agatha by this proceeding.

07:05.380 --> 07:06.720
He did not succeed.

07:07.380 --> 07:11.960
They remained confined for five months before the trial took place, the result of which

07:11.960 --> 07:16.100
deprived them of their fortune and condemned them to a perpetual exile from their native

07:16.100 --> 07:16.680
country.

07:17.600 --> 07:21.900
They found a miserable asylum in the cottage in Germany, where I discovered them.

07:22.460 --> 07:27.180
Felix soon learned that the treacherous Turk for whom he and his family endured such unheard

07:27.180 --> 07:32.360
of oppression on discovering that his deliverer was thus reduced to poverty and ruin, became

07:32.360 --> 07:36.860
a traitor to good feeling and honor, and had quitted Italy with his daughter, insultingly

07:36.860 --> 07:41.900
sending Felix a pittance of money to aid him, as he said, in some plan of future maintenance.

07:43.180 --> 07:47.100
Such were the events that preyed on the heart of Felix and rendered him, when I first saw

07:47.100 --> 07:49.300
him, the most miserable of his family.

07:49.880 --> 07:53.880
He could have endured poverty, and while this distress had been the mead of his virtue,

07:54.300 --> 07:55.200
he gloried in it.

07:55.540 --> 07:59.760
But the ingratitude of the Turk and the loss of his beloved safety were misfortunes more

07:59.760 --> 08:00.940
bitter and irreparable.

08:01.600 --> 08:05.320
The arrival of the Arabian now infused new life into his soul.

08:06.760 --> 08:11.020
When the news reached Leghorn that Felix was deprived of his wealth and rank, the merchant

08:11.020 --> 08:14.800
commanded his daughter to think no more of her lover but to prepare to return to her

08:14.800 --> 08:15.500
native country.

08:16.100 --> 08:20.760
The generous nature of safety was outraged by this command, she attempted to expostulate

08:20.760 --> 08:25.100
with her father, but he left her angrily, reiterating his tyrannical mandate.

08:26.100 --> 08:30.620
A few days after, the Turk entered his daughter's apartment and told her hastily that he had

08:30.620 --> 08:34.700
reason to believe that his residence at Leghorn had been divulged, and he should speedily

08:34.700 --> 08:36.220
be delivered up to the French government.

08:36.900 --> 08:41.580
He had consequently hired a vessel to convey him to Constantinople, for which city he should

08:41.580 --> 08:42.620
sail in a few hours.

08:42.620 --> 08:47.140
He intended to leave his daughter under the care of a confidential servant, to follow

08:47.140 --> 08:50.840
at her leisure with the greater part of his property, which had not yet arrived at Leghorn.

08:51.400 --> 08:56.220
When alone, safety resolved in her own mind, the plan of conduct that it would become her

08:56.220 --> 08:57.520
to pursue in this emergency.

08:58.200 --> 09:00.180
A residence in Turkey was abhorrent to her.

09:00.520 --> 09:03.460
Her religion and her feelings were alike averse to it.

09:04.100 --> 09:08.840
By some papers of her father which fell into her hands, she heard of the exile of her lover,

09:09.140 --> 09:11.360
and learnt the name of the spot where he then resided.

09:11.930 --> 09:15.620
She hesitated some time, but at length she formed her determination.

09:16.360 --> 09:20.520
Taking with her some jewels that belonged to her, and a sum of money, she quitted Italy

09:20.520 --> 09:25.040
with an attendant, a native of Leghorn, but who understood the common language of Turkey,

09:25.360 --> 09:26.560
and departed for Germany.

09:27.200 --> 09:31.920
She arrived in safety at a town about twenty leagues from the cottage of De Lacey, when

09:31.920 --> 09:33.920
her attendant felt dangerously ill.

09:34.840 --> 09:39.440
Safety nursed her with the most devoted affection, but the poor girl died, and the Arabian was

09:39.440 --> 09:43.660
left alone, unacquainted with the language of the country, and utterly ignorant of the

09:43.660 --> 09:44.440
customs of the world.

09:45.300 --> 09:47.140
She fell, however, into good hands.

09:47.720 --> 09:51.380
The Italian had mentioned the name of the spot for which they were bound, and after

09:51.380 --> 09:55.560
her death the woman of the house in which they lived took care that safety should arrive

09:55.560 --> 09:57.480
in safety at the cottage of her lover.

09:59.040 --> 10:03.000
Chapter 15 Such was the history of my beloved cottagers.

10:03.660 --> 10:05.000
It impressed me deeply.

10:05.600 --> 10:10.780
I learned from the views of social life which it developed to admire their virtues and to

10:10.780 --> 10:12.360
deprecate the vices of mankind.

10:13.500 --> 10:18.600
As yet I looked upon crime as a distant evil, benevolence and generosity were ever present

10:18.600 --> 10:23.640
before me, inciting within me a desire to become an actor in the busy scene where so

10:23.640 --> 10:26.460
many admirable qualities were called forth and displayed.

10:27.460 --> 10:32.100
But in giving an account of the progress of my intellect I must not omit a circumstance

10:32.100 --> 10:35.260
which occurred in the beginning of the month of August of the same year.

10:36.040 --> 10:40.340
One night during my accustomed visit to the neighboring woods where I collected my own

10:40.340 --> 10:45.920
food and brought home firing for my protectors, I found on the ground a leathern portmanteau

10:45.920 --> 10:48.660
containing several articles of dress and some books.

10:50.060 --> 10:53.520
I eagerly seized the prize and returned with it to my hovel.

10:54.060 --> 10:57.820
Fortunately the books were written in the language, the elements of which I had acquired

10:57.820 --> 10:58.560
at the cottage.

10:59.040 --> 11:05.000
They consisted of Paradise Lost, a volume of Plutarch's Lives and the Sorrows of Werther.

11:05.860 --> 11:08.460
The possession of these treasures gave me extreme delight.

11:09.020 --> 11:13.560
I now continually studied and exercised my mind upon these histories whilst my friends

11:13.560 --> 11:15.840
were employed in their ordinary occupations.

11:16.580 --> 11:19.020
I can hardly describe to you the effect of these books.

11:19.580 --> 11:25.320
They produced in me an infinity of new images and feelings that sometimes raised me to ecstasy

11:25.320 --> 11:28.160
but more frequently sunk me into the lowest ejection.

11:28.960 --> 11:34.580
In the Sorrows of Werther, besides the interest of its simple and affecting story, so many

11:34.580 --> 11:39.180
opinions are canvassed and so many lights thrown upon what had hitherto been to me obscure

11:39.180 --> 11:44.160
subjects that I found in it a never-ending source of speculation and astonishment.

11:44.940 --> 11:49.900
The gentle and domestic manner as it described, combined with lofty sentiments and feelings

11:49.900 --> 11:55.060
which had for their object something out of self, accorded well with my experience among

11:55.060 --> 11:59.260
my protectors and with the wants which were forever alive in my own bosom.

12:00.020 --> 12:05.220
But I thought Werther himself was a more divine being than I had ever beheld or imagined.

12:05.660 --> 12:09.140
His character contained no pretension, but it sank deep.

12:09.840 --> 12:14.060
The disquisitions upon death and suicide were calculated to fill me with wonder.

12:14.680 --> 12:19.620
I did not pretend to enter into the merits of the case, yet I inclined towards the opinions

12:19.620 --> 12:24.360
of the hero whose extinction I wept without precisely understanding it.

12:25.260 --> 12:29.980
As I read, however, I applied much personally to my own feelings and condition.

12:30.600 --> 12:35.540
I found myself similar, yet at the same time strangely unlike to the beings concerning

12:35.540 --> 12:38.360
whom I read and to whose conversation I was a listener.

12:38.940 --> 12:43.760
I sympathized with and partly understood them, but I was unformed in mind.

12:44.080 --> 12:46.600
I was dependent on none and related to none.

12:47.200 --> 12:52.220
The path of my departure was free, and there was none to lament my annihilation.

12:52.960 --> 12:56.120
My person was hideous, and my stature gigantic.

12:56.820 --> 12:57.900
What did this mean?

12:58.420 --> 12:59.260
Who was I?

12:59.400 --> 13:00.200
What was I?

13:00.620 --> 13:01.700
Whence did I come?

13:02.280 --> 13:03.600
What was my destination?

13:04.500 --> 13:08.440
These questions continually recurred, but I was unable to solve them.

13:09.340 --> 13:13.780
The volume of Plutarch's Lives, which I possessed, contained the histories of the first founders

13:13.780 --> 13:15.300
of the ancient republics.

13:15.300 --> 13:18.600
This book had a far different effect on me from the sorrows of Werther.

13:19.040 --> 13:24.120
I learned from Werther's imaginations, despondency, and gloom, but Plutarch taught me high thoughts.

13:24.460 --> 13:29.200
He elevated me above the wretched sphere of my own reflections to admire and love the

13:29.200 --> 13:30.360
heroes of past ages.

13:31.120 --> 13:34.120
Many things I read surpassed my understanding and experience.

13:34.680 --> 13:39.220
I had a very confused knowledge of kingdoms, wide extensive country, mighty rivers and

13:39.220 --> 13:44.660
boundless seas, but I was perfectly unacquainted with towns and large assemblages of men.

13:44.660 --> 13:49.080
The cottage of my protectors had been the only school in which I had studied human nature,

13:49.480 --> 13:52.440
but this book developed new and mightier scenes of action.

13:53.400 --> 13:57.880
I read of men concerned in public affairs, governing or massacring their species.

13:58.400 --> 14:03.780
I felt the greatest ardor for virtue rise within me, and aberrance for vice, as far

14:03.780 --> 14:08.140
as I understood the signification of those terms, relative as they were, as I applied

14:08.140 --> 14:09.760
them, to pleasure and pain alone.

14:10.520 --> 14:16.520
Induced by these feelings, I was of course led to admire peaceable lawgivers, Numa, Salin,

14:16.640 --> 14:19.760
and Lycurgus, in preference to Romulus and Thesis.

14:20.320 --> 14:24.940
The patriarchal lives of my protectors caused these impressions to take a firm hold on my

14:24.940 --> 14:25.220
mind.

14:25.600 --> 14:30.420
Perhaps, if my first introduction to humanity had been made by a young soldier burning for

14:30.420 --> 14:33.840
glory and slaughter, I should have been imbued with different sensations.

14:34.400 --> 14:38.460
But Paradise Lost excited different and far deeper emotions.

14:38.860 --> 14:43.040
I read it, as I'd read the other volumes which had fallen into my hands, as a true

14:43.040 --> 14:43.540
history.

14:44.260 --> 14:48.700
It moved every feeling of wonder and awe that the picture of an omnipotent god warring with

14:48.700 --> 14:50.440
his creatures was capable of exciting.

14:51.180 --> 14:55.780
I often referred the several situations, as their similarities struck me, to my own.

14:56.420 --> 15:01.540
Like Adam, I was apparently united by no link to any other being in existence.

15:02.220 --> 15:05.320
But his state was far different from mine in every other respect.

15:05.320 --> 15:10.860
He had come forth from the hands of a god, a perfect creature, happy and prosperous,

15:11.280 --> 15:13.380
guarded by the especial care of his creator.

15:13.700 --> 15:17.500
He was allowed to converse with and acquire knowledge from beings of a superior nature,

15:17.520 --> 15:20.080
but I was wretched, helpless, and alone.

15:20.820 --> 15:26.160
Many times I considered Satan as the fitter emblem of my condition, for often, like him,

15:26.380 --> 15:31.020
when I viewed the bliss of my protectors, the bitter gall of envy rose within me.

15:32.320 --> 15:35.060
Another circumstance strengthened and confirmed these feelings.

15:35.460 --> 15:40.100
Soon after my arrival in the hovel, I discovered some papers in the pocket of the dress which

15:40.100 --> 15:41.440
I had taken from your laboratory.

15:42.040 --> 15:46.160
At first I had neglected them, but now that I was able to decipher the characters in

15:46.160 --> 15:49.060
which they were written, I began to study them with diligence.

15:49.980 --> 15:52.920
It was your journal of the four months that preceded my creation.

15:53.580 --> 15:58.120
You minutely described in these papers every step you took in the progress of your work.

15:58.460 --> 16:01.720
This history was mingled with accounts of domestic occurrences.

16:02.180 --> 16:03.780
You doubtless recollect these papers.

16:04.240 --> 16:04.940
Here they are.

16:05.400 --> 16:08.800
Everything is related in them which bears reference to my accursed origin.

16:09.280 --> 16:14.100
The whole detail of that series of disgusting circumstances which produced it is set in

16:14.100 --> 16:14.320
view.

16:14.820 --> 16:19.500
The minutest description of my odious and loathsome person is given, in language which

16:19.500 --> 16:22.260
painted your own horrors and rendered mine indelible.

16:22.940 --> 16:24.180
I sickened as I read.

16:24.180 --> 16:27.920
Hateful day when I received life, I exclaimed in agony.

16:28.740 --> 16:33.440
A cursed creator, why did you form a monster so hideous that even you turned from me in

16:33.440 --> 16:33.800
disgust?

16:34.500 --> 16:39.780
God, in pity, made man beautiful and alluring after his own image, but my form is a filthy

16:39.780 --> 16:42.760
type of yours, more horrid even from the very resemblance.

16:43.400 --> 16:47.900
Satan had his companions, fellow devils, to admire and encourage him, but I am solitary

16:47.900 --> 16:48.720
and abhorred.

16:49.360 --> 16:52.840
These were the reflections of my hours of despondency and solitude.

16:52.840 --> 16:58.540
But when I contemplated the virtues of the cottagers, their amiable and benevolent dispositions,

16:58.820 --> 17:03.560
I persuaded myself that when they should become acquainted with my admiration of their virtues,

17:03.940 --> 17:07.420
they would compassionate me and overlook my personal deformity.

17:08.020 --> 17:12.540
Could they turn from their door one, however monstrous, who solicited their compassion

17:12.540 --> 17:13.140
and friendship?

17:13.640 --> 17:18.820
I resolved at least not to despair, but in every way to fit myself for an interview with

17:18.820 --> 17:20.380
them which would decide my fate.

17:21.140 --> 17:25.840
I postponed this attempt for some months longer, for the importance attached to its success

17:25.840 --> 17:28.680
inspired me with a dread lest I should fail.

17:29.720 --> 17:34.540
Besides, I found that my understanding improved so much with every day's experience that I

17:34.540 --> 17:38.720
was unwilling to commence this undertaking until a few more months could have added to

17:38.720 --> 17:39.440
my sagacity.

17:40.360 --> 17:42.860
Several changes in the meantime took place in the cottage.

17:43.540 --> 17:48.720
The presence of Saffi diffused happiness among its inhabitants, and I also found that a greater

17:48.720 --> 17:50.300
degree of plenty reigned there.

17:50.820 --> 17:55.360
Felix and Agatha spent more time in amusement and conversation, and were assisted in their

17:55.360 --> 17:56.280
labors by servants.

17:56.900 --> 18:00.180
They did not appear rich, but they were contented and happy.

18:00.520 --> 18:05.500
Their feelings were serene and peaceful, while mine became every day more tumultuous.

18:06.720 --> 18:11.540
Increase of knowledge only discovered to me more clearly what a wretched outcast I was.

18:12.160 --> 18:17.620
A cherished hope, it's true, but it vanished when I beheld my person reflected in water

18:17.620 --> 18:23.220
or my shadow in the moonshine, even as that frail image and that inconstant shade.

18:24.200 --> 18:28.900
I endeavored to crush these fears and to fortify myself for the trial which in a few months

18:28.900 --> 18:34.640
I resolved to undergo, and sometimes I allowed my thoughts, unchecked by reason, to ramble

18:34.640 --> 18:39.940
in the fields of paradise, and dared to fancy amiable and lovely creatures sympathizing

18:39.940 --> 18:42.100
with my feelings and cheering my gloom.

18:42.400 --> 18:45.740
Their angelic countenances breathed smiles of consolation.

18:45.740 --> 18:47.800
But it was all a dream.

18:48.460 --> 18:51.100
No Eve soothed my sorrows nor shared my thoughts.

18:51.500 --> 18:52.260
I was alone.

18:53.320 --> 18:57.320
I remembered Adam's supplication to his Creator, but where was mine?

18:57.760 --> 19:01.980
He had abandoned me, and in the bitterness of my heart I cursed him.

19:02.860 --> 19:03.800
Autumn passed thus.

19:04.380 --> 19:09.700
I saw with surprise and grief the leaves decay and fall, and nature again assumed the barren

19:09.700 --> 19:13.400
and bleak appearance it had worn when I first beheld the woods and the lovely moon.

19:13.400 --> 19:15.980
Yet I did not heed the bleakness of the weather.

19:16.280 --> 19:20.120
I was better fitted by my confirmation for the endurance of cold than heat.

19:20.920 --> 19:24.500
But my chief delights were the sight of the flowers, the birds, and all the gay apparel

19:24.500 --> 19:24.960
of summer.

19:25.440 --> 19:29.240
When those deserted me, I turned with more attention towards the cottagers.

19:29.900 --> 19:32.600
Their happiness was not decreased by the absence of summer.

19:33.000 --> 19:37.420
They loved and sympathized with one another, and their joys, depending on each other, were

19:37.420 --> 19:40.120
not interrupted by the casualties that took place around them.

19:40.120 --> 19:44.700
The more I saw of them, the greater became my desire to claim their protection and kindness.

19:45.020 --> 19:49.420
My heart yearned to be known and loved by these amiable creatures, to see their sweet

19:49.420 --> 19:54.120
looks directed towards me with affection was the utmost limit of my ambition.

19:55.060 --> 19:58.380
I dared not think that they would turn them from me with disdain and horror.

19:58.920 --> 20:01.340
The poor that stopped at their door were never driven away.

20:01.880 --> 20:05.940
I asked, it is true, for greater treasures than a little food or rest.

20:05.940 --> 20:11.580
I required kindness and sympathy, but I did not believe myself utterly unworthy of it.

20:12.520 --> 20:16.880
The winter advanced, and an entire revolution of the seasons had taken place since I awoke

20:16.880 --> 20:17.520
into life.

20:17.980 --> 20:22.040
My attention at this time was solely directed towards my plan of introducing myself into

20:22.040 --> 20:23.420
the cottage of my protectors.

20:24.240 --> 20:28.560
I revolved many projects, but that on which I finally fixed was to enter the dwelling

20:28.560 --> 20:30.320
when the blind old man should be alone.

20:30.900 --> 20:35.400
I had sagacity enough to discover that the unnatural hideousness of my person was the

20:35.400 --> 20:38.420
object of horror with those who had formerly beheld me.

20:38.980 --> 20:42.300
My voice, although harsh, had nothing terrible in it.

20:42.760 --> 20:46.560
I thought, therefore, that if in the absence of his children I could gain the goodwill

20:46.560 --> 20:51.840
and mediation of the old De Lacy, I might by his means be tolerated by my younger protectors.

20:52.860 --> 20:57.500
One day, when the sun shone on the red leaves that strewed the ground in diffused cheerfulness,

20:58.040 --> 21:03.080
although it denied warmth, Safie, Agatha, and Felix departed on a long country walk,

21:03.080 --> 21:06.520
and the old man, at his own desire, was left alone in the cottage.

21:07.340 --> 21:11.700
When his children had departed, he took up his guitar and played several mournful but

21:11.700 --> 21:15.420
sweet airs, more sweet and mournful than I had ever heard him play before.

21:16.260 --> 21:21.000
At first his countenance was illuminated with pleasure, but as he continued, thoughtfulness

21:21.000 --> 21:22.080
and sadness succeeded.

21:22.580 --> 21:26.120
At length, laying aside the instrument, he sat absorbed in reflection.

21:27.220 --> 21:28.340
My heart beat quick.

21:28.720 --> 21:33.660
This was the hour and moment of trial which would decide my hopes and realize my fears.

21:34.220 --> 21:36.140
The servants were gone to a neighboring fair.

21:36.540 --> 21:38.460
All was silent in and around the cottage.

21:38.520 --> 21:43.740
It was an excellent opportunity, yet when I proceeded to execute my plan, my limbs failed

21:43.740 --> 21:44.980
me and I sank to the ground.

21:45.680 --> 21:50.140
Again I rose, and exerting all the firmness of which I was master, removed the planks

21:50.140 --> 21:52.600
which I had placed before my hovel to conceal my retreat.

21:53.400 --> 21:58.220
The fresh air revived me, and with renewed determination, I approached the door of their cottage.

21:59.180 --> 21:59.720
I knocked.

22:01.160 --> 22:02.320
Who is there?

22:02.800 --> 22:03.660
said the old man.

22:04.020 --> 22:04.800
Come in.

22:05.980 --> 22:06.500
I entered.

22:07.560 --> 22:09.040
Pardon this intrusion, I said.

22:09.540 --> 22:11.460
I am a traveler in want of a little rest.

22:12.140 --> 22:15.880
You would greatly oblige me if you would allow me to remain a few minutes before the fire.

22:17.300 --> 22:22.320
Enter, said Delacy, and I will try in what manner I can to relieve your wants, but unfortunately

22:22.320 --> 22:26.380
my children are from home, and as I am blind, I am afraid I should find it difficult to

22:26.380 --> 22:27.540
procure food for you.

22:28.220 --> 22:30.380
Oh, do not trouble yourself, my kind host.

22:30.500 --> 22:31.300
I have food.

22:31.660 --> 22:33.620
It is warmth and rest only that I need.

22:34.680 --> 22:37.480
I sat down, and a silence ensued.

22:38.260 --> 22:42.360
I knew that every minute was precious to me, yet I remained irresolute in what manner to

22:42.360 --> 22:43.280
commence the interview.

22:44.000 --> 22:48.640
When the old man addressed me, By your language, stranger, I suppose you are my countryman.

22:48.720 --> 22:49.360
You are French?

22:50.720 --> 22:54.920
No, but I was educated by a French family, and understand that language only.

22:55.560 --> 23:00.140
I am now going to claim the protection of some friends whom I sincerely love, and of

23:00.140 --> 23:01.460
whose favor I have some hopes.

23:02.220 --> 23:03.100
Are they Germans?

23:04.160 --> 23:07.160
No, they are French, but let us change the subject.

23:07.560 --> 23:09.540
I am an unfortunate and deserted creature.

23:10.000 --> 23:12.680
I look around, and I have no relation or friend upon earth.

23:13.060 --> 23:17.180
These amiable people to whom I go have never seen me, and know little of me.

23:17.180 --> 23:22.120
I am full of fears, for if I fail there, I am an outcast in the world forever.

23:23.660 --> 23:24.600
Oh, do not despair.

23:25.040 --> 23:29.260
To be friendless is indeed unfortunate, but the hearts of men, when unprejudiced by any

23:29.260 --> 23:32.460
obvious self-interest, are full of brotherly love and charity.

23:33.280 --> 23:38.180
Rely therefore on your hopes, and if these friends are good and amiable, do not despair.

23:39.880 --> 23:40.800
They are kind.

23:40.900 --> 23:44.480
They are the most excellent creatures in the world, but unfortunately they are prejudiced

23:44.480 --> 23:45.100
against me.

23:45.480 --> 23:46.820
I have good dispositions.

23:46.820 --> 23:51.580
My life has been hitherto harmless, and in some degree beneficial, but if fatal prejudice

23:51.580 --> 23:56.160
clouds their eyes, and when they ought to see a feeling and kind friend, they behold

23:56.160 --> 23:57.720
only a detestable monster.

23:59.220 --> 24:04.500
That is indeed unfortunate, but if you are really blameless, cannot you undeceive them?

24:05.620 --> 24:10.620
I am about to undertake that task, and it is on that account that I feel so many overwhelming

24:10.620 --> 24:11.340
terrors.

24:11.800 --> 24:13.400
I tenderly love these friends.

24:13.400 --> 24:17.860
I have, unknown to them, been for many months in the habits of daily kindness toward them,

24:18.220 --> 24:22.480
but they believe that I wish to injure them, and that is the prejudice which I wish to

24:22.480 --> 24:22.920
overcome.

24:24.600 --> 24:25.820
Where do these friends reside?

24:27.080 --> 24:28.040
Near this spot.

24:29.340 --> 24:31.120
The old man paused, and then continued,

24:32.140 --> 24:36.820
If you will unreservedly confide to me the particulars of your tale, I perhaps may be

24:36.820 --> 24:38.060
of use in undeceiving them.

24:38.340 --> 24:42.440
I am blind, and cannot judge of your countenance, but there is something in your words which

24:42.440 --> 24:44.040
persuades me that you are sincere.

24:44.720 --> 24:50.000
I am poor and in exile, but it will afford me true pleasure to be in any way serviceable

24:50.000 --> 24:51.000
to a human creature.

24:52.560 --> 24:55.840
Excellent man, I thank you and accept your generous offer.

24:56.360 --> 25:00.840
You raise me from the dust by this kindness, and I trust that by your aid I shall not be

25:00.840 --> 25:03.660
driven from the society and sympathy of your fellow creatures.

25:04.580 --> 25:09.640
Heaven forbid, even if you were really criminal, for that can only drive you to desperation

25:09.640 --> 25:11.200
and not instigate you to virtue.

25:11.760 --> 25:13.600
I also am unfortunate.

25:13.960 --> 25:16.840
I and my family have been condemned, although innocent.

25:17.500 --> 25:20.680
Judge therefore if I do not feel for your misfortunes.

25:21.740 --> 25:24.740
How can I thank you, my best and only benefactor?

25:25.360 --> 25:28.960
From your lips first have I heard the voice of kindness directed toward me.

25:29.180 --> 25:33.420
I shall be forever grateful, and your present humanity assures me of success with those

25:33.420 --> 25:35.060
friends whom I am on the point of meeting.

25:36.260 --> 25:38.780
May I know their names and residence of those friends?

25:39.780 --> 25:40.740
I paused.

25:41.680 --> 25:46.320
This, I thought, was the moment of decision, which was to rob me of or bestow happiness

25:46.320 --> 25:47.100
on me forever.

25:48.100 --> 25:53.080
I struggled vainly for firmness sufficient to answer him, but the effort destroyed all

25:53.080 --> 25:54.040
my remaining strength.

25:54.480 --> 25:56.440
I sank on the chair and sobbed aloud.

25:57.660 --> 26:00.220
At that moment I heard the steps of my younger protectors.

26:00.260 --> 26:05.780
I had not a moment to lose, but seizing the hand of the old man, I cried, Now is the time.

26:06.180 --> 26:07.400
Save and protect me.

26:07.560 --> 26:10.240
You and your family are the friends whom I seek.

26:11.100 --> 26:13.200
Do not you desert me in the hour of trial?

26:14.140 --> 26:15.160
Great, God!

26:15.600 --> 26:16.440
exclaimed the old man.

26:16.520 --> 26:17.560
Who are you?

26:18.420 --> 26:23.300
At that instant the cottage door was opened, and Felix, Safie, and Agatha entered.

26:24.280 --> 26:27.620
Who can describe their horror and consternation on beholding me?

26:28.580 --> 26:32.840
Agatha fainted, and Safie, unable to attend to her friend, rushed out of the cottage.

26:33.400 --> 26:38.600
Felix darted forward, and with supernatural force tore me from his father, to whose knees

26:38.600 --> 26:39.260
I clung.

26:39.720 --> 26:43.940
In a transport of fury he dashed me to the ground and struck me violently with a stick.

26:44.840 --> 26:49.540
I could have torn him limb from limb as the lion rinsed the antelope, but my heart sank

26:49.540 --> 26:52.380
within me as with bitter sickness, and I refrained.

26:53.520 --> 26:58.680
I saw him on the point of repeating his blow, when, overcome by pain and anguish, I quitted

26:58.680 --> 27:03.120
the cottage, and in the general tumult escaped unperceived to my hovel.

